<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-10-23T22:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-10-23T22:00:00-05:00" n="885" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d885">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">893.102S/2336: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-10-24T10:00:00+07:00">October 24, 1940—10
                                        a.m.</date><lb/>[Received 10:18 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>542. Department’s 179, October 21, 5 p.m. While I am not hopeful of
                                any cooperation from the Japanese side, I think that it would be
                                wise to explore matter of courts privately with the Japanese Consul
                                General before discussing matter with colleagues. I am certain that
                                Chinese Government consent beforehand will not be forthcoming but
                                believe that after the matter has been accomplished it will
                                interpose nothing more than <hi rend="italic">pro forma</hi>
                                objection.</p>
                            <p>Sent to the Department. Repeated to Peiping, Shanghai.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>